A better year for migrants?
DUBLIN – Two major lessons emerge from the migration crisis in the Mediterranean.
First, Europe and the international community are applying a cruelly inadequate system for protecting the most vulnerable migrants.
Secondly, in the face of the ineffectiveness of this system, populist actors keep exploiting fears to gain political support, undermining liberal and tolerant societies whose construction required some 70 years of determined effort.
This is why it is essential that this year a genuinely active approach be undertaken at the European and global levels.
In September, UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will convene an extraordinary summit aimed at building a strong global system for protecting the most destitute migrants and refugees.
Let us hope that states will be ready to commit in a concrete and sustainable manner.
This necessary commitment was sadly lacking during the year 2015.
In fact, the international community could have limited the severity of last year's crisis if it had provided even the most minimal support to the frontline countries – Turkey, Lebanon, and Jordan – which together host no fewer than four million refugees.
With only about 10 billion euros, these countries would have been better able to house, feed, and provide education for refugees, thus reducing the temptation to flee to Europe.
This failure could cost Germany up to 21 billion € each year in the coming years.
But the financial implications of the crisis are incomparable to its human and political cost.
Over a million people risked their lives last year by crossing the Mediterranean, enduring a exhausting journey through the Balkans afterwards.
Nearly 4,000 migrants lost their lives there, while many European countries turned their backs on the survivors by refusing to grant them asylum.
The most cynical political actors have mercilessly exploited citizens' fears, promoting an odious nationalist vision that either ignores or distorts the lived experiences of migrants.
In the United States, for example, not a single one of the 780,000 refugees settled since September 11, 2001, has been found guilty of engaging in terrorist activities.
At the same time, immigrants generally pay more taxes than they receive in social benefits.
Yet, extremist parties are dangerously flirting with gaining political power in some European countries, and are currently gaining support even within once-liberal strongholds.
Anti-immigration parties are already in power in Hungary and Poland.
Their success is also leading traditional parties to promote their own anti-immigration policies.
This situation has seriously undermined European cooperation.
The EU program aimed at dealing with the million refugees who arrived on its shores only managed to "relocate" 190.
Border controls in six countries belonging to the Schengen area have been reinstated, at least temporarily.
To the rest of the world, the EU now appears chauvinistic and incompetent.
Of course, resolving this crisis is not only Europe's concern; responsibility cannot be defined by mere geographical proximity.
Regardless, the EU is likely facing a threat to its own existence today, which it can only overcome by firmly demonstrating the solidarity and international leadership it is capable of.
That is why it is up to the member states to take the initiative by proposing solutions.
The most urgent priority is to establish legal and safe pathways allowing refugees to reach Europe.
This is not to say that every migrant in difficulty must be welcomed.
Nonetheless, it is up to the EU to be more systematically generous in determining the number of refugees to accept, and to employ ordered mechanisms to facilitate their entry.
Such a system would allow migrants to be protected while safeguarding Europe (through the possibility of thoroughly examining asylum requests).
Beyond a measure aimed at deterring asylum seekers from risking their lives by crossing the Mediterranean, such an approach would also project an image of solidarity towards frontline countries, which continue to host the majority of refugees.
An equally important aspect, this approach would encourage the rest of the international community to contribute to the efforts.
This leads us to the second priority of 2016: building a strong global system for protecting vulnerable refugees and migrants.
This goal will first require that more countries agree to accept refugees.
The UN Refugee Agency has only managed to resettle less than 75,000 of the approximately 20 million refugees annually.
Many of them end up in a situation of prolonged migration, with an average duration estimated at 25 years, trapped in a sort of purgatory and uncertain about the day of a possible return to their country.
In 2016, it is necessary for developed countries to commit to hosting a cumulative number close to one million refugees each year, either through resettlement or by granting them a humanitarian, student, professional, or other visa.
Canada having stated that it will host 50,000 Syrian refugees this year, this is a clearly achievable goal.
At the same time, the international community will need to support the integration of refugees in major host countries such as Turkey, Kenya, Lebanon, and Jordan.
In the current situation, these countries receive only a fraction of the $3,000 to $5,000 annually needed per refugee for housing, food, care, education, and vocational training during the first years of settlement.
And these figures do not include the necessary cost of building or upgrading infrastructure.
In Lebanon, for example, water supply systems are suffering from the pressure caused by the massive arrival of refugees.
In exchange for funding, these host countries could commit to fully integrating refugees into their schools, labor markets, and civic institutions.
But effective integration of migrants will only be possible if European and other countries rid themselves of their prejudices about migrants.
If these groups remain seen as a burden, or even as a threat to security, reactionary political forces will continue to gain ground, depriving new arrivals of opportunities and turning fear into a self-fulfilling prophecy.
On the contrary, if host countries manage to integrate migrants enthusiastically, everyone will benefit – including these countries (notably through inflows of money).
Last month, in Paris, the international community proved that it was capable of subordinating national interests to a broader global objective: the fight against climate change.
In 2016, it is necessary that a similar effort aims to build a better system for protecting migrants.
This is a matter of life or death for some 20 million refugees, for several millions of other vulnerable migrants – as well as a profound test of the civic health of democratic societies around the world.
